That's what the original movies were talking about. Every movie after has been an attempt to deny how necessary that change is. Either the commentary is forgotten, or the responsibility is shoved off on someone else. And without that heart, the movies just aren't that good.
We know it's bad, we know it will destroy us, and yet we keep on doing it. That is the definition of human nature, and the thing we as a species most need to change if we want to survive.

--it is something visited upon us by a third party. It goes from being something we need to change to something that we simply need to survive. The nebulous mystery of the Xenomorph's origin is what allows it to be metaphorical, and is what damns our pursuit of it.

I also think that it's a mistake to have David be the creator of the Xenomorph, because if the violence metaphor is a good one, having David make them absolves humanity of responsibility. Instead of the violence being something that we carry with us, that ultimately ends us--

This is also probably why Covenant gets kind of close to the original formula. There is a very close bond between the crew members, and the stuff between David and Walter is pretty damn good...but then we veer off into the lore, and the Engineers and the black fluid.

You see it in how much of the original two movies were about the relationships and connections that Ripley has, and how the fuel for Isolation was not some great revelation about the Aliens' origin, but Amanda Ripley's connection to her mother.

That's why it does not matter if the Xenomorph was engeneered by an AI, or by the Predator aliens, or if it sprung fully formed from Zeus's brow. The Xenomorph is just a stand in for the systemic violence that humanity just can't seem to shake.

The Alien franchise is ultimately about the human race carrying the violence and horror of our present into our future. It's as much about what we do to each other as it is about what the alien does to us.

If Scifi is about the future, The Alien franchise is about what that future will look like if we don't change. A lot of people see the Xenomorph as a rape metaphor. But I'd say it's a violence metaphor, of which rape is a component.

And that, I believe, is where the real heart of the franchise lies. Because it's not about the Aliens. Trying to make the series be about the aliens is why it has fucked up so consistently. The aliens are not important. What is important is the fear and violence surrounding them.

Alien, Aliens, and Alien: Isolation are exactly the opposite. They are exceptionally pessimistic. The environments are very much like what we would see today. There's sexism, racism, violence, and people are mostly controlled by the corporations that govern them.

And while the franchise itself has plenty of issues with sexism and racism (Because it isn't made in that future, it only dreams about it) It is at its best when it relies on its hopeful roots (Which is largely why its movies fail to equal the TV shows; the hope is forgotten)

Star Trek, for example, is very positive. Optimistic. It sets forth a future of clean lines and benevolent government, where racism and sexism and all the other 'isms have been successfully conquered,and violence is no longer an every-day thing.

Second: It tells me what the original movies and the game are really about. My personal theory is that where Fantasy fiction is about ourselves and our inner worlds, Scifi is about, well, the future. Where are we headed? Where is the technology going? What will we be like?

Which tells me a couple things: First, what resonated with people in the first two movies wasn't the lore, it wasn't the idea of aliens, and it especially was not the violence of humans shooting Aliens. All of those things are what the franchise movies have focused on.

The game follows Ripley's daughter as she tries to figure out what happened to the Nostromo. She winds up on a mostly abandoned station, and the few people she meets will kill her just as quick as the Alien. It doesn't add a whole lot to the franchise lore, but it gets it right.

Alien: Isolation nailed the formula you saw in the first two movies. That game is TERRIFYING, as in there's only so long you can play it. There are guns in it and you can use them, but you're dead if you do. A lot of the gameplay is simply leaning around corners and listening.

Basically every movie after Aliens leaves you wondering why they keep missing the formula that made the first two movies so damn good and scary. That was my major question, until I saw the one place where somebody finally got it right. And it wasn't a movie.
--if they hadn't had to waste so much time explaining how David developed the xenomorph for...reasons that make no fucking sense.

Covenant and Prometheus are objectively good movies, but instead of reviving Xenomorphs, the movies are weighed down by them. David's character in Covenant, and his interactions with Walter (Fuck you for breaking the AI naming convention, BTW) would be much better--

And Covenant...same thing. It had a lot of good pieces that belonged together...in another movie. Xenomorphs had a little bit more relevance but you could still cut them out and spackle the holes over without losing too much movie. Which IMHO means they didn't belong there.

Prometheus rebooted it, but it became obsessed with both the Engeneers (Which is a great concept that belongs in another movie) and the AIs going off the rails (David=Ash from the first movie). It had a lot of little interesting bits that...never really came together.

The third movie, however, completely lost the fucking plot. We have the prison-monks, Newt and the other survivors from Aliens are fridged basically offscreen, Ripley is bald, there's violence and aliens, and the movie never really comes together. Alien 4 had the same problem.

It's something that has kind of mystified me. Alien was a good movie. Aliens was a masterpiece, even more-so if you put the scene where Ripley is told her daughter grew old and died while she was in cryosleep. It explains the trauma bond between Riply and Newt so much better.
